@Node "Documentation Files" "filenameguide.guide/Documentation Files"
@Next "Binaries"
@Prev "File Names"
@Toc "File Names"

Documentation Files
===================

Documentation files may only be located in the directory @{b}UMS/Doc/@{ub}.  In
this directory are several subdirectories for different languages.  The
suffix of the file name specifies the type of the document file:

.dvi
     DVI

.guide
     AmigaGuide

.tex
     TeX

.texi
     Texinfo

.txt
     ASCII

Example:
     @{b}UMS/Doc/english/IntuiNews.guide@{ub}
     @{b}UMS/Doc/deutsch/UMSprog.txt@{ub}

   Additional files, like @{b}README@{ub} files, should not placed in @{b}UMS/Doc/@{ub}
but in the directory @{b}UMS/(tools|networks|reader)/<application name>/@{ub}
(see @{"Application Directories" Link "Application Directories"}). The other (beloved :) extra file is the
@{b}History@{ub} file, which should be included in the main documentation file.

   This main documentation file should be in AmigaGuide format. If there
are several formats of this document and if installaton is executed by
Installer, the user should be asked which format shall be installed in
the directory @{b}UMS/Doc/@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "Binaries" "filenameguide.guide/Binaries"
@Next "Application Directories"
@Prev "Documentation Files"
@Toc "File Names"

Binaries
========

All programs and AmigaDOS script files are located in the directory
@{b}UMS/Bin/@{ub}. This makes it easy for the user to start them, because he
only has to add @{b}Path UMS/Bin Add@{ub} or @{b}Assign C: UMS/Bin Add@{ub} to his
startup scripts.


@EndNode

@Node "Application Directories" "filenameguide.guide/Application Directories"
@Prev "Binaries"
@Toc "File Names"

Application Directories
=======================

The directories @{b}Networks/@{ub}, @{b}Reader/@{ub} and @{b}Tools/@{ub} contain the application
packages for the UMS project. Every application has its own
subdirectory.

   Example:
     @{b}UMS/Networks/FTN/@{ub}
     @{b}UMS/Networks/Maus/@{ub}
     @{b}UMS/Networks/QWK/@{ub}
     @{b}UMS/Networks/RFC/@{ub}
     @{b}UMS/Networks/Zer/@{ub}

The application packages have several uniform directories for the
different file types:

@{b}src/@{ub}
     Source code

@{b}doc/@{ub}
     Other files or formats of the (main) documentation file which is
     located in @{b}UMS/doc/@{ub}. See @{"Documentation Files" Link "Documentation Files"}, for more details.

Example:
     @{b}UMS/Networks/RFC/src/uucpexporter/DMakefile@{ub}
     @{b}UMS/Reader/IntuiNews/doc/deutsch/IntuiNews.dvi@{ub}


@EndNode

@Node "Developer Directory" "filenameguide.guide/Developer Directory"
@Next "Application Archives"
@Prev "File Names"
@Toc "Main"

Developer Directory
*******************

If a package includes the source code for the program then the
programmer can use the knowledge about the UMS directory in his
Makefiles. He can use relative path names, e.g. @{b}INCDIR =
////Developer/c/include@{ub}. This eases the compilation process for the
user.

   Directory @{b}Developer/@{ub}:
@{b}UMS/Developer/c/@{ub}
     Subdirectory for C

@{b}UMS/Developer/c/dlib/@{ub}
     Link libraries for DICE

@{b}UMS/Developer/c/dlib/ums/@{ub}
     Source for the DICE link libraries

@{b}UMS/Developer/c/examples/ums/@{ub}
     Example programs in C

@{b}UMS/Developer/c/include/clib/@{ub}
     Function prototypes

@{b}UMS/Developer/c/include/libraries/@{ub}
     Include files

@{b}UMS/Developer/c/include/pragmas/@{ub}
     Declarations for inline calls

@{b}UMS/Developer/c/include/proto/@{ub}
     Proto files

@{b}UMS/Developer/c/slib/@{ub}
     Link libraries for SAS/C

@{b}UMS/Developer/c/slib/ums/@{ub}
     Source for the SAS/C link libraries

@{b}UMS/Developer/doc/deutsch/@{ub}
     Documentation in German

@{b}UMS/Developer/doc/english/@{ub}
     Documentation in Englisch

@{b}UMS/Developer/fd/@{ub}
     FD files

@{b}UMS/Developer/m2/@{ub}
     Subdirectory for Modula-2

@{b}UMS/Developer/m2/examples/@{ub}
     Example programs in Modula-2

@{b}UMS/Developer/oberon/@{ub}
     Subdirectory for Oberon

@{b}UMS/Developer/oberon/examples/@{ub}
     Example programs in Oberon


@EndNode

@Node "Application Archives" "filenameguide.guide/Application Archives"
@Next "Authors"
@Prev "Developer Directory"
@Toc "Main"

Application Archives
********************

Archives should use the same directory structure as the @{b}UMS@{ub} directory.
This makes the installation process very easy, because the user just
has to unpack the archive and the files will be located in their
correct directory. The archives should not contain any files which
belong to other UMS archives.

   Example:
     1> @{b}lha vq UMSRFC1_0.lha@{ub}
     UMS/Bin/ums2uucp
     UMS/Bin/uuxqt
     ...
     UMS/Doc/english/umsrfc.guide
     ...
     UMS/Libs/umsrfc.library
     ...
     UMS/Networks/RFC/src/nntpserver/DMakefile
     UMS/Networks/RFC/doc/english/umsrfc.dvi
     UMS/Networks/RFC/doc/english/umsrfc.txt
     ...

Please make sure, that there are no icons (#?.info files) for
directories. The user can have icons already installed and, if she is
unpacking the archive, "her" old icons will be overwritten.

   The name of the archive should start with @{b}UMS@{ub}. If there is no danger
of mixing it up with another application then this prefix may be left
out. The name should always include the version, revision and the patch
level (one lowercase letter) of the application. They should be
appended to the name of the package like this:

     @{i}<version>_<revision><patch level>@{ui}

The last element of the name is the suffix for the archive format.

   Example:
     @{b}UMSConf3_0.lzx@{ub}
     @{b}IntuiNews2_0a.lha@{ub}
     @{b}Umsrfc1_0.tar@{ub}
     @{b}UMS12_1.tgz@{ub}


@EndNode

